sounds interesting.

00:00:42.669 --> 00:00:43.710
Can I hear more about it?

00:00:43.710 --> 00:00:44.585
MATT HENDERSON: Yeah.

00:00:44.585 --> 00:00:47.190
So there's really
two different things

00:00:47.190 --> 00:00:48.940
that we're launching
within the app model.

00:00:48.940 --> 00:00:51.590
So one is the
Android app bundle.

00:00:51.590 --> 00:00:54.470
That's a new format,
a publishing format,

00:00:54.470 --> 00:00:57.920
that a developer can use
that enables him to reduce

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:00.230
the size of their app.

00:01:00.230 --> 00:01:04.819
The Android app bundle makes
use of a Play technology--

00:01:04.819 --> 00:01:06.680
Play dynamic delivery.

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:11.990
And together, it
serves the optimal APK

00:01:11.990 --> 00:01:14.540
for a user's given device.

00:01:14.540 --> 00:01:19.580
And so it optimizes for the
user-specific CPU architecture

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:20.690
of their device.

00:01:20.690 --> 00:01:24.440
It optimizes for their
screen densities.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:28.160
It optimizes for
the user's languages

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:29.580
that they speak as well.

00:01:29.580 --> 00:01:33.950
And so by only sending the parts
of the bundle that the user

00:01:33.950 --> 00:01:37.790
actually needs, it means that
the APK that goes to the device

00:01:37.790 --> 00:01:39.020
is a lot smaller.

00:01:39.020 --> 00:01:41.900
And that, in turn,
enables much better

00:01:41.900 --> 00:01:46.520
install conversion rates,
enables lower uninstall rates.

00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:49.684
Because when the app sizes are
too big, users react badly.

00:01:49.684 --> 00:01:52.100
And so that's something we're
launching today that I think

00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:53.980
is going to be a big
win for developers.

